{
  "answer": "**Ghalib compares the world (*duniya*) to a \"children's game\" (*bazicha-e-atfal*) in the matla (opening couplet) of ghazal chapter 213.**[^1]\n\nThis is from the first verse of *Diwan-E-Ghalib*:\n\n> This world is but a children's game, a vast display,  \n> Where night and day a spectacle unfolds my way.[^1]\n\n\"Bazicha-e-atfal\" literally evokes a \"playhouse of children,\" \"children's toys,\" or \"playground for kids\"—a metaphor portraying worldly existence as illusory and childlike spectacle, a recurring theme in his philosophical reflections.[^2]\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/213-baazeecha-e-atfaal-hai-duniya-mere-aage/translation/#p-3132be).\n[^2]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [chapter](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/213-baazeecha-e-atfaal-hai-duniya-mere-aage/translation/).",
